ACT IV. Scmm V.

In this scene we have the eontinuation and success of Syrus’s pro- ject. Chremes, agreeably to his character of a good-natured and friendly man, is here introduced, expressing his concern for his neigh- bour Menedemus, to whose lot it is now fallen to feel the weight of this expensive train; and the more so, as he foresees that he is likely to continue under the burden for some time. While thus musing, he perceives Syrus, and renews the former conversation about deceiving Menedemus: to which Syrus gives so artful a turn, as to

persuade him to give with his own hands the money to Clitipho, and uorder him to carry it to Bacchis.
